WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:08.240
<v Teacher>So, we're looking at <i>-ar</i> verbs and how they work, and we are changing them for the different people.

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:10.000
<v Teacher>Let's make a recap.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:12.960
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>to contaminate</i>?

00:00:13.340 --> 00:00:14.300
<v Student><b>Contaminar.</b>

00:00:14.300 --> 00:00:14.620
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:14.620 --> 00:00:17.660
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>it's contaminating</i>?

00:00:18.140 --> 00:00:19.180
<v Student><b>Contamina.</b>

00:00:19.180 --> 00:00:19.500
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:22.220
<v Teacher>So our key vowel for <i>-ar</i> verbs is /a/.

00:00:22.220 --> 00:00:23.500
<v Teacher>That's our key vowel.

00:00:23.500 --> 00:00:31.100
<v Teacher>We add an <i>n</i> to get <i>you guys</i> or <i>they contaminate</i>. So how would that be?

00:00:31.100 --> 00:00:32.300
<v Student><b>Contaminan.</b>

00:00:32.300 --> 00:00:33.820
<v Teacher><b>Contaminan.</b> Good.

00:00:34.220 --> 00:00:38.860
<v Teacher>And we add an <i>s</i> to the <i>he/she/it</i> form to get the <i>you</i> (informal).

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:41.980
<v Teacher>So <i>you</i> (informal) <i>contaminate</i> would be:

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:44.320
<v Student><b>Contaminas.</b>

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:52.400
<v Teacher>Now for <i>-er/-ir</i> verbs, for <i>-er/-ir</i> verbs, their key sound is /e/.

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:57.280
<v Teacher>For this closed group of historic verbs, their key sound is /e/.

00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:00.760
<v Teacher>So, what do you think <b>vender</b> means?

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:03.560
<v Teacher><b>Vender</b>. What do you think that means?

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:06.840
<v Student>Does it have anything to do with <i>vent</i> and <i>ventilation</i>?

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:08.039
<v Teacher>No it's not a <i>t</i>, it's a <i>d</i>.

00:01:08.039 --> 00:01:10.200
<v Student>Oh <i>vending</i>. <i>Vending machine</i>?

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:10.840
<v Teacher>Yeah.

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:11.079
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:11.079 --> 00:01:12.759
<v Teacher>So what does it mean then, <b>vender</b>?

00:01:12.759 --> 00:01:15.240
<v Teacher>What does a vending machine do?

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:17.000
<v Teacher>It's a selling machine.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.960
<v Teacher>Or you might have heard <i>street vender</i> as well.

00:01:19.960 --> 00:01:23.240
<v Teacher>So <i>I sell</i> or <i>I'm selling:</i>

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:24.120
<v Student><b>Vendo.</b>

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:26.600
<v Teacher><i>I'm selling it:</i>

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:28.420
<v Student><b>Lo vendo</b>?

00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:29.460
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:33.540
<v Teacher>Is there anywhere else you can put that <b>lo</b>? Do you have the option here?

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:37.740
<v Student>Well, we can put it at the end if it's in its <b>vender</b> state.

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:40.860
<v Teacher>Exactly. So no, we can't put it anywhere else. It has to go there.

00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:41.659
<v Teacher><b>Lo vendo.</b>

00:01:41.659 --> 00:01:44.540
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I'm selling them</i>?

00:01:44.940 --> 00:01:46.140
<v Student><b>Lo vendas.</b>

00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:51.200
<v Teacher>It's very important when you're making-

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:51.200
<v Student><b>Véndolo. Las.</b> Oh. Sorry.

00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:57.520
<v Teacher>It's very important when you're building the sentence that you take your time to understand who's doing what.

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:01.680
<v Teacher><i>I sell</i>, it's me doing the selling.

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:02.960
<v Teacher>So <i>I'm selling them</i>,

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:05.360
<v Teacher>the first bit you want to work out is <i>I'm selling</i>.

00:02:05.360 --> 00:02:06.800
<v Teacher>What's that?

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:07.840
<v Student><b>Vendo.</b>

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:08.160
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:09.840
<v Teacher>And then you want to work out <i>them</i>.

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:11.520
<v Teacher><i>I sell</i> is <b>vendo</b>. <i>I sell them</i> is?

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:15.760
<v Student><b>Los vendo.</b>

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:16.640
<v Teacher><b>Los vendo.</b>

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:16.960
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:19.760
<v Teacher>So this process of dividing it into two thoughts,

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:24.180
<v Teacher>just doing that is going to make sure that you don't kind of get this salad.

00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:29.860
<v Teacher>Many times, you will just switch them, and you want to say <i>she has them</i> but you will say <i>they have her</i>.

00:02:29.860 --> 00:02:33.620
<v Teacher>You know, so it's very important to take your time to think about those bits separately.

00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:37.620
<v Teacher>If you're talking about feminine things like <i>I sell the houses</i>, how would it be?

00:02:37.620 --> 00:02:40.820
<v Teacher>So it's still <i>them</i> we're going to say, but we mean feminine things.

00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:41.700
<v Teacher><i>I sell them:</i>

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:45.420
<v Student><b>Las vendo.</b>

00:02:45.420 --> 00:02:46.220
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:47.420
<v Teacher><b>Las vendo.</b>

00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:52.460
<v Teacher>If you want to say actually <i>I sell</i> or <i>I am selling the houses</i>,

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:57.520
<v Teacher>the word for <i>the</i>, we said was <b>la</b>. <b>La casa</b> also becomes plural.

00:02:57.520 --> 00:02:58.240
<v Student><b>Las.</b>

00:02:58.240 --> 00:02:58.720
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:01.280
<v Teacher>And the word <b>casa</b> also becomes plural.

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:02.080
<v Student><b>Casas.</b>

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:03.920
<v Teacher>So <i>I am selling the houses:</i>

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:06.420
<v Student><b>Vendo las casas</b>?

00:03:06.420 --> 00:03:07.860
<v Teacher>Yeah. <i>I'm selling the houses</i>,

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:12.420
<v Teacher><b>vendo las casas</b>, or <i>I'm selling them</i> and you mean the houses:

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:14.140
<v Student><b>Las vendo.</b>

00:03:14.140 --> 00:03:15.100
<v Teacher><b>Las vendo.</b>

00:03:15.100 --> 00:03:15.420
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:15.420 --> 00:03:25.900
<v Teacher>The reason why we're looking at this with objects is because many people, when they're learning Spanish, they remember to change gender for people, but they kind of put all things in with <b>lo</b> and <b>los</b>

00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:28.519
<v Teacher>and we kind of want to get out of that habit before it starts.

00:03:28.519 --> 00:03:31.640
<v Teacher>So we imagine the houses, we refer to them as <b>las</b>.

00:03:31.640 --> 00:03:37.319
<v Student>Is there a rule for which objects are female and which are not?

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:43.400
<v Teacher>Well remember it's not strictly the object that has the gender, but the word, the noun in itself.

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:46.680
<v Teacher>So feminine words end in <i>a</i>.

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:49.319
<v Teacher>Words that end in <i>a</i>, with a few exceptions, are feminine words.

00:03:49.319 --> 00:03:53.000
<v Teacher>So <b>casa</b> is feminine: <b>la casa</b>. And it takes <b>la</b>.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.800
<v Teacher>Then there are other feminine endings.

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:58.440
<v Teacher>So <i>-ión</i> is a feminine ending.

00:03:58.599 --> 00:04:02.040
<v Teacher><i>The administration</i> is <b>la administración</b>.

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:04.200
<v Teacher>All of these words are going to be <b>la</b>.

00:04:04.200 --> 00:04:05.480
<v Teacher><i>The opinion</i> is?

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:08.239
<v Student><b>La opinión.</b>

00:04:08.239 --> 00:04:09.920
<v Teacher><b>La opinión.</b>

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:13.040
<v Teacher><i>The association:</i>

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:14.640
<v Student><b>La asociación.</b>

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:15.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:16.880
<v Teacher><i>The celebration:</i>

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:18.879
<v Student><b>La celebración.</b>

00:04:18.879 --> 00:04:20.239
<v Teacher><b>La celebración.</b>

00:04:20.239 --> 00:04:20.879
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:20.879 --> 00:04:25.919
<v Teacher>If a word ends in <i>-ity</i> in English, it's going to be <i>-idad</i>

00:04:25.539 --> 00:04:27.699
<v Teacher>in Spanish most of the time.

00:04:27.699 --> 00:04:30.419
<v Teacher>This <i>-idad</i> is a feminine ending as well.

00:04:30.419 --> 00:04:34.020
<v Teacher>So that shows us that all of these words are feminine words.

00:04:33.539 --> 00:04:40.259
<v Teacher>So for example you have <i>diversity</i>. You change that <i>-ity</i> to <i>-idad</i>.

00:04:40.259 --> 00:04:41.780
<v Teacher><i>-idad</i>.

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:42.819
<v Student><b>Diversidad.</b>

00:04:42.819 --> 00:04:43.220
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:44.340
<v Teacher><b>Diversidad</b>.

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:45.699
<v Teacher><i>The diversity:</i>

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:49.160
<v Student><b>La diversidad.</b>

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:53.880
<v Teacher><b>La diversidad.</b> Good. <i>The nationality:</i>

00:04:55.860 --> 00:04:57.220
<v Student><b>La nacionalidad.</b>

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:01.860
<v Teacher>The same happens with the <i>-tion</i>, it becomes like an <i>s</i> or a /th/ in most of Spain.

00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:04.820
<v Teacher><b>La na/s/ionalidad</b>, <b>la na/th/ionalidad</b>,

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:06.340
<v Teacher>you could hear either.

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:08.340
<v Teacher><i>The creativity:</i>

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:10.760
<v Student><b>La creatividad.</b>

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:11.800
<v Teacher>Very well pronounced.

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:13.640
<v Teacher>You thought of the vowels very well.

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:15.400
<v Teacher><b>La creatividad</b>.

00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:17.640
<v Teacher><i>The electricity:</i>

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:20.040
<v Student><b>La electricidad.</b>

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:21.479
<v Teacher><b>La electricidad.</b>

00:05:21.479 --> 00:05:24.759
<v Teacher>These words are very nice as well for guessing other words.

00:05:24.759 --> 00:05:29.960
<v Teacher>Because if you have this rule, <i>electricity</i> becomes <b>electricidad</b>,

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:40.000
<v Teacher>you can assume that <i>electric</i> is probably the same in Spanish as well, just sounding more Spanish or having a small change. Even though there's no rule for that,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:41.040
<v Teacher>you can assume it.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:43.200
<v Teacher>So how do you think you would say <i>electric</i>?

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:44.800
<v Student><b>ElecTRIC.</b>

00:05:45.120 --> 00:05:46.320
<v Teacher>Does it sound Spanish enough yet?

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:47.120
<v Student><b>ElecTRIco.</b>

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:47.680
<v Teacher>Yeah

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:48.560
<v Teacher><b>eLECtrico.</b>

00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:49.360
<v Student><b>Eléctrico.</b>

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:50.640
<v Teacher><b>Eléctrico.</b>

00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:53.120
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>generosity</i>?

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:56.080
<v Student><b>Generosidad.</b>

00:05:56.080 --> 00:05:57.360
<v Teacher>Very good. <b>Generosidad.</b>

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:59.520
<v Teacher>How do you think you will say <i>generous</i>?

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:01.040
<v Teacher>Have a play with it.

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:05.920
<v Student><b>Gener</b>…

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:06.240
<v Teacher>Have a play with it and see what sits nice.

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:07.360
<v Student><b>Generoso.</b>

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:09.040
<v Teacher>Yes. <b>Generoso.</b>

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:10.000
<v Teacher><b>Generoso.</b>

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:10.800
<v Teacher>For males.

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:13.680
<v Teacher>For females what do you think it would become?

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:15.060
<v Student><b>Generosa.</b>

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:15.860
<v Teacher><b>Generosa.</b>

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:19.620
<v Teacher>Exactly. How <b>lo</b> becomes <b>la</b>, <b>generoso</b> becomes <b>generosa</b>.

00:06:19.620 --> 00:06:24.740
<v Teacher>It also can become plural as well if we're talking about more than one person, male or mixed group,

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:26.340
<v Teacher>how would it sound?

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:27.600
<v Student><b>Generosos.</b>

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:27.920
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:31.360
<v Teacher>And if I was just speaking about females?

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:32.320
<v Student><b>Generosas.</b>

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:33.520
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:35.040
<v Teacher><i>Community:</i>

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:36.880
<v Student><b>Comunidad.</b>

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:39.280
<v Teacher>Good. <i>The community:</i>

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:40.240
<v Student><b>La comunidad.</b>

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:41.200
<v Teacher><b>La comunidad.</b>

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:42.720
<v Teacher>Feminine word, feminine ending.

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:46.560
<v Teacher>How do you think you would say <i>common</i>? <i>Common</i> comes from <i>community</i>, by the way.

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:48.500
<v Student>Is it <b>cómono</b>? <b>Comono.</b>

00:06:50.580 --> 00:06:51.860
<v Teacher><b>Común.</b>

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:52.740
<v Student>Ah.

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:53.380
<v Teacher>So there's no way to know that.

00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:55.220
<v Student><b>Comuno</b> or <b>Común</b>?

00:06:55.220 --> 00:06:56.020
<v Teacher><b>Común</b>.

00:06:56.020 --> 00:06:57.300
<v Student>It's irregular?

00:06:57.300 --> 00:06:58.340
<v Teacher>There's no rule here

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:00.500
<v Teacher>so there's no irregularity.

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:06.580
<v Teacher>So maybe you will take <b>comuno</b> and somebody would give you that feedback of <b>común</b>. And then you would realize.

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:09.140
<v Teacher>But if you didn't take that guess, you wouldn't get the word.

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:12.020
<v Teacher>We will learn a lot of vocabulary very quickly this way.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:14.560
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>opportunity</i>?

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:16.240
<v Student><b>Oportunidad.</b>

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:19.440
<v Teacher>How do you think you would say <i>opportune</i>?

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:20.000
<v Teacher><i>Opportune</i>,

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.520
<v Teacher>you know we use this word in English like <i>timely</i> or <i>convenient</i>.

00:07:23.520 --> 00:07:25.040
<v Teacher><i>Opportune:</i>

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:26.680
<v Student><b>Oportuna</b>?

00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:27.560
<v Teacher><b>Oportuno.</b>

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:28.120
<v Student><b>Oportuno.</b>

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:31.720
<v Teacher>Or if you are talking about a feminine thing, <b>oportuna</b>.

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:33.160
<v Teacher><i>Clarity:</i>

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:34.480
<v Student><b>Claridad.</b>

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:35.600
<v Teacher><b>Claridad.</b>

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:37.760
<v Teacher>And <i>clear</i> comes from <i>clarity</i>.

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:41.840
<v Teacher>So you can look at <b>claridad</b> and you can probably guess how to say <i>clear</i>.

00:07:42.180 --> 00:07:43.060
<v Student><i>Clear</i>?

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:46.100
<v Teacher>But look at the Spanish word. <b>Claridad.</b>

00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:47.460
<v Student><b>Clarido.</b>

00:07:47.460 --> 00:07:49.700
<v Teacher>And the <i>-idad</i> is the ending isn't it?

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:50.820
<v Student>Oh yes, <b>claro</b>.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:51.700
<v Teacher>Yes,

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:52.160
<v Teacher><b>claro</b>.

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:54.240
<v Teacher>So this is another good skill.

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:56.400
<v Teacher>When you're guessing, you want to get rid of the ending.

00:07:56.400 --> 00:07:58.720
<v Teacher>This ending <i>-idad</i> is what's making it a noun.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:00.080
<v Teacher><b>La claridad</b>.

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:00.960
<v Teacher><b>Claro.</b>

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:03.360
<v Teacher>And <b>claro</b> is used a lot

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:13.020
<v Teacher>conversationally. Other than meaning "clear" as an adjective, it can also be used like "of course". <b>Claro, claro, claro.</b> You will hear this a lot

00:08:13.039 --> 00:08:18.639
<v Teacher>in conversation to show agreement or understanding of what you've said.

00:08:18.639 --> 00:08:20.159
<v Teacher><b>Claro.</b>

00:08:20.159 --> 00:08:21.360
<v Teacher><i>Personality:</i>

00:08:22.520 --> 00:08:23.639
<v Student><b>Personalidad.</b>

00:08:23.639 --> 00:08:24.440
<v Teacher><b>Personalidad.</b>

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:28.120
<v Teacher>So we can assume that <i>person</i> is probably the same in Spanish as well.

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:30.280
<v Teacher>When I say "the same", I mean similar.

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:31.720
<v Student>So again it's guessing. It could be-

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:34.020
<v Teacher>Exactly. So what do you think it sounds like?

00:08:34.340 --> 00:08:36.340
<v Teacher>You will develop an intuition, especially through listening.

00:08:36.340 --> 00:08:43.620
<v Teacher>This is why listening is important as well because this is what will really develop your intuition. Because you might have heard it before and not realized it.

00:08:42.959 --> 00:08:45.600
<v Student>I've heard of <b>persona</b>, so I'm guessing it's <b>persono</b>.

00:08:45.600 --> 00:08:46.480
<v Teacher>It's <b>persona</b>.

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:47.360
<v Student>Oh <b>persona.</b>

00:08:47.519 --> 00:08:48.560
<v Teacher>It's <b>persona</b>.

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:49.760
<v Teacher>It's a feminine word.

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:52.720
<v Teacher>So remember it's the word that's feminine or masculine, not the thing.

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:55.120
<v Teacher>So I am a <b>persona</b>,

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:58.800
<v Teacher>even though I am a man. The word is feminine, not me.

00:08:58.800 --> 00:09:01.200
<v Teacher><i>Sincerity:</i>

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:02.320
<v Student><b>Sinceridad.</b>

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:03.440
<v Teacher><b>Sinceridad.</b>

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:04.240
<v Teacher><i>Sincere:</i>

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:06.660
<v Student><b>Sencero.</b>

00:09:06.660 --> 00:09:07.380
<v Teacher><b>Sincero.</b>

00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:08.020
<v Student><b>Sincero.</b>

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:14.740
<v Teacher><b>Sincero.</b> So that's another example of a feminine ending. If it ends <i>-idad</i>, it's a feminine ending.

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:17.060
<v Teacher>All of these words without exception are <b>la</b>.

00:09:17.060 --> 00:09:19.860
<v Teacher>If it ends <i>-ión</i>, that's a feminine ending.

00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:22.580
<v Teacher>All of these words without exceptions go with <b>la</b>.

00:09:22.580 --> 00:09:24.019
<v Teacher>Back to <b>vender</b>.

00:09:24.019 --> 00:09:25.940
<v Teacher>How was <i>I sell</i>?

00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:26.980
<v Student><b>Vendo.</b>

00:09:26.980 --> 00:09:29.380
<v Teacher><i>I want to sell:</i>

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:30.900
<v Student><b>Quiero vender.</b>

00:09:31.860 --> 00:09:32.180
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:32.180 --> 00:09:33.700
<v Teacher><i>I want to sell it:</i>

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:35.180
<v Student><b>Quiero venderlo.</b>

00:09:35.180 --> 00:09:35.700
<v Teacher><b>Quiero venderlo.</b>

00:09:36.180 --> 00:09:38.340
<v Teacher>Where else could we put that <b>lo</b>?

00:09:38.500 --> 00:09:39.860
<v Student><b>Lo quiero vender.</b>

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:40.500
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:45.860
<v Teacher>The <i>-er/-ir</i> verbs use as their principal sound /e/.

00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:49.300
<v Teacher>So whilst <i>-ar</i> verbs use the principle sound /a/,

00:09:49.839 --> 00:09:56.639
<v Teacher>and we got <b>organizar</b> and then <b>organiza</b>, for - what does that mean, <b>organiza</b>?

00:09:56.639 --> 00:09:59.199
<v Student><i>He/she</i> or <i>it</i>

00:09:59.980 --> 00:10:02.060
<v Student>or <i>you</i> (formal).

00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:02.540
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:05.420
<v Teacher>So <b>organiza</b>, /a/ is a principal sound.

00:10:05.420 --> 00:10:09.340
<v Teacher><b>Organizan</b> means? When we add an <i>n</i> what does it mean?

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:10.480
<v Student><i>They.</i>

00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:11.680
<v Teacher><i>They organize</i>.

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:12.800
<v Teacher>Or?

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:14.800
<v Student><i>You</i> (plural).

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:16.240
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (plural).

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:19.360
<v Teacher>So we add the <i>n</i> and we get <i>they</i> and <i>you guys</i>.

00:10:20.560 --> 00:10:23.120
<v Teacher>We add the <i>s</i> and we get <i>you</i> (informal),

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:25.040
<v Teacher><b>organizas</b>.

00:10:25.040 --> 00:10:30.640
<v Teacher>So /a/ is our key sound for <i>-ar</i> verbs, and for <i>-er/-ir</i> verbs, our key sound is /e/.

00:10:30.339 --> 00:10:37.300
<v Teacher>So to get <i>he/she/it</i> and <i>you</i> formal, we'll take off our ending and put on /e/.

00:10:37.300 --> 00:10:41.380
<v Teacher><i>He sells, she sells, it sells, you</i> (formal) <i>sell:</i>

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:42.920
<v Student><b>Vende.</b>

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:43.800
<v Teacher><b>Vende.</b>

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:47.800
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>he sells it</i> or <i>she sells it</i>?

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:50.120
<v Student><b>Lo vende.</b>

00:10:50.120 --> 00:10:50.520
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:50.520 --> 00:10:52.720
<v Teacher><b>Lo vende.</b> <b>Lo vende.</b>

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:55.279
<v Teacher>We said that the word for <i>something</i> was <b>algo</b>,

00:10:55.279 --> 00:10:55.920
<v Teacher><b>algo</b>.

00:10:55.920 --> 00:11:00.319
<v Teacher>So you can say <i>he's selling something</i>, <i>she's selling something</i>, <i>you're selling something</i>.

00:11:01.300 --> 00:11:02.820
<v Student><b>Vende algo.</b>

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:03.220
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:04.660
<v Teacher><b>Vende algo.</b>

00:11:04.660 --> 00:11:05.860
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:05.860 --> 00:11:12.820
<v Teacher>What do you think we would add on to <b>vende</b> to get the <i>they</i> form or the <i>you</i> (plural) form?

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:14.420
<v Student><b>Venden.</b>

00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:15.700
<v Teacher>So we're doing actually the same.

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:18.420
<v Teacher>So we have a key vowel sound, which is /e/.

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:21.940
<v Teacher>But then the rest, we're doing the same what we did with the <i>-ar</i> verbs.

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:22.660
<v Teacher><b>Venden</b>.

00:11:22.660 --> 00:11:23.140
<v Teacher><i>They sell</i>.

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:24.900
<v Teacher><i>They're not selling:</i>

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:26.199
<v Student><b>No venden.</b>

00:11:26.199 --> 00:11:28.440
<v Teacher><i>They're not selling it:</i>

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:29.880
<v Student><b>No lo venden.</b>

00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:31.959
<v Teacher><i>Why aren't they selling it?:</i>

00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:34.340
<v Student><b>¿Por qué no lo venden?</b>

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:34.660
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:34.660 --> 00:11:36.420
<v Teacher><b>¿Por qué no lo venden?</b>

00:11:36.420 --> 00:11:38.340
<v Teacher><i>Why aren't they selling it to me?</i>,

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:40.740
<v Teacher>you just say <i>why aren't they selling me it?</i>

00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:43.540
<v Teacher>You put the personal one, <i>me</i>, first.

00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:46.340
<v Teacher>The one that refers to the person it goes first.

00:11:46.340 --> 00:11:48.980
<v Teacher>You just say <i>why aren't they selling me it?</i>

00:11:49.220 --> 00:11:51.860
<v Teacher>So <i>they are selling</i>. How is <i>they are selling</i>?

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:53.960
<v Student><b>Venden.</b>

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:54.600
<v Teacher><b>Venden.</b>

00:11:54.600 --> 00:11:56.680
<v Teacher><i>They are selling it:</i>

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:57.880
<v Student><b>Lo venden.</b>

00:11:57.880 --> 00:11:58.200
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:58.200 --> 00:11:59.480
<v Teacher><i>They are selling me it.</i>

00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:03.080
<v Teacher>So they come together and the personal one comes first.

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:05.440
<v Student><b>Me lo venden.</b>

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:06.400
<v Teacher><b>Me lo venden.</b>

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:10.800
<v Teacher>So whilst we have this complicated stuff happening in English, <i>they sell it to me</i>,

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:13.840
<v Teacher>no, in Spanish we're just going to identify it's <i>it</i> and it's <i>me</i>,

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:16.160
<v Teacher><i>me</i> is the personal one so it's going to come first,

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:17.920
<v Teacher><b>me lo venden</b>.

00:12:17.820 --> 00:12:19.180
<v Teacher><i>They're selling it to me.</i>

00:12:19.180 --> 00:12:20.540
<v Teacher><i>They're not selling it to me</i>,

00:12:20.540 --> 00:12:23.340
<v Teacher>or <i>they don't sell it to me:</i>

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:24.780
<v Student><b>No me lo venden.</b>

00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:26.220
<v Teacher><b>No me lo venden.</b>

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:28.380
<v Teacher><i>Why don't they sell it to me?</i>

00:12:28.380 --> 00:12:30.339
<v Student><b>¿Por qué no me lo venden?</b>

00:12:30.339 --> 00:12:31.300
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:12:31.300 --> 00:12:34.180
<v Teacher>The word for <i>us</i> is <b>nos</b>.

00:12:34.180 --> 00:12:35.940
<v Teacher><b>Nos</b>, the word for <i>us</i>.

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:41.620
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>they are selling us something</i>?

00:12:41.259 --> 00:12:46.139
<v Teacher>So <i>something</i>, you know <b>algo</b>, is not one of these little words like <b>me</b>, <b>lo</b>, <b>nos</b>.

00:12:46.139 --> 00:12:47.980
<v Teacher>It's going to come afterwards.

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:50.779
<v Teacher>So <i>they are selling us something:</i>

00:12:52.980 --> 00:12:55.380
<v Student><b>Nos venden algo.</b>

00:12:55.380 --> 00:12:56.260
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:12:56.260 --> 00:12:58.420
<v Teacher><b>Nos venden algo.</b>

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:04.500
<v Teacher>But if instead of saying <i>they're selling us something</i> and you just wanted to say <i>they're selling us it</i>,

00:13:04.560 --> 00:13:06.000
<v Teacher><i>they're selling it to us</i>,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:07.440
<v Teacher><i>they're selling us it</i>.

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:10.640
<v Teacher>How would it be?

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:12.880
<v Student><b>Nos lo venden.</b>

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:13.520
<v Teacher>Good.

00:13:13.459 --> 00:13:14.740
<v Teacher><b>Nos lo venden.</b>

00:13:14.740 --> 00:13:14.980
<v Teacher>Good.

00:13:14.980 --> 00:13:17.700
<v Teacher>So there you have an <i>us</i>, you have an <i>it</i>, you have a <i>they</i>.

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:24.100
<v Teacher>It could be like hugely complicated, no, if you just took that all as a package and tried to translate it.

00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:26.500
<v Teacher>But thinking about the verb first

00:13:25.940 --> 00:13:32.340
<v Teacher>then you're thinking about the other bits you need to put, then you get the sentence that you want, confident that you have the sentence that you want.

00:13:32.340 --> 00:13:36.020
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>they're not selling it to us</i>?

00:13:38.300 --> 00:13:40.620
<v Student><b>No nos lo venden.</b>

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:41.020
<v Teacher>Good.

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:42.860
<v Teacher><b>No nos lo venden.</b>

00:13:42.860 --> 00:13:45.340
<v Teacher><i>Why don't they sell it to us?</i>

00:13:46.340 --> 00:13:49.860
<v Student><b>¿Por qué no nos lo venden?</b>

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:50.340
<v Teacher>Good. <b>¿Por qué no nos lo venden?</b> Very good.
